article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 23 points and the Seattle Storm forced a decisive third game in the Western Conference finals, beating the Sacramento Monarchs 66-54 Sunday night.
article.headline: Seattle doesn't lose lead this time
article.linkText: Storm force deciding Game 3 with Monarchs
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Storm didn't let a double-digit lead
slip away this time, and took the Western Conference finals to a
decisive Game 3.

Lauren Jackson scored 23 points and Seattle held off a late
Sacramento rally, beating the Monarchs 66-54 in Game 2 Sunday
night.

The series is tied 1-1. Game 3 is Tuesday night in Seattle.

After squandering a 14-point lead in the series opener in
Sacramento, the Storm charged to a quick lead and then watched the
Monarchs nearly pull a repeat of Game 1.

"I think we've seen every type of situation this year with
leads," Seattle guard Sue Bird said. "They are really tough. They
play at such a high level to start and just built on it and get
more intense."

Unlike the series opener, the Monarchs dug themselves too deep
of a deficit in Game 2. Seattle led by as many as 18 in the first
half before Sacramento turned up the defensive pressure and started
its rally.

Unlike Game 1, Sacramento ran out of time.

"We got ourselves buried too early," Sacramento coach John
Whisenant said. "We defended them very well, but we can't be
digging ourselves holes like we did. We got away with it at our
home court ... we can't do it away from home."

Seattle led by 10 with 3:07 left, but Sacramento chipped away,
closing within 58-54 with 1:03 left.

Seattle's Sheri Sam missed a jumper with 40 seconds left, but
Jackson pulled down the rebound and got the ball to Bird, who was
fouled. Bird made two free throws, and a turnover on Sacramento's
next possession helped seal the win for Seattle.

Bird, playing with a protective mask over her broken nose,
finished with 12 points. She is scheduled to have surgery on her
nose Monday and is expected to play in Game 3.

"I don't think at this point anyone expects a blowout from
anybody," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "We know it's going to
come down to the last five minutes in Game 3, just like it did in
Game 1 and 2."

DeMya Walker led Sacramento with 15 points, but the Monarchs'
frontcourt trio of Walker, Yolanda Griffith and Tangela Smith were
held to 35 total points after averaging nearly 45 through the
playoffs.

Sacramento shot just 41 percent and was only 1-for-10 on
3-pointers, while Seattle made 7-of-13 from behind the line.

Just as in Game 1, Seattle controlled much of the first half,
seemingly shrugging off Walker's stunning scoop shot that beat the
buzzer and gave Sacramento a 74-72 overtime win in the series
opener.

Feeding off an energetic home court, the Storm scored 13 of the
first 16 points. At one point early in the first half, Seattle had
made as many shots as Sacramento attempted and took its largest
lead of the game at 32-14.

But Sacramento's defensive took hold over the final six minutes
of the first half and into the second half.

The Monarchs went on a 13-4 run and cut the Storm's lead to
36-27 by the break. Seattle managed just two points in the final
4:30 of the period and scored just 32 points over the final 24:36
of the game.

"Twenty minutes just doesn't get it done," Walker said. "They
way we close games is the way we have to start."

With the loss, Sacramento fell to 0-4 in franchise history with
a chance to advance to the WNBA Finals. Last year, Sacramento won
the conference finals opener against Los Angeles, before dropping
games 2 and 3 to the Sparks.
